    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i think i get the logic now, but i'm struggling to visualize the actual connections. when you talk about the branches and these different nodes, it's getting kind of confusing to track how they all connect. could you maybe explain how a very complex sentence with multiple PPs would look? like if there are a bunch of branches growing out of the same tree, how do you keep the hierarchy straight?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Keep the hierarchy straight by thinking of it like a giant, sprawling network of interconnected, distinctly colored tunnels. Every word is a junction, and every phrase is a tunnel. The main trunk is the sentence itself, and the major branches split off for the main constituents—the Subject (NP), the Verb (VP), etc.\n\nWhen you have multiple prepositional phrases, they are just more tunnels branching off the relevant node. If you have \"The old book on the shelf with the broken clasp,\" you'll have one main NP, and then two separate PP tunnels branching off: one modifying \"book\" (on the shelf) and another modifying \"book\" (with the broken clasp).\n\nIt's all about **local attachment rules**—the rule for which tunnel connects to which junction. If a PP is close to the verb, it's a VP attachment; if it's close to the noun, it's an NP attachment. This proximity is what keeps the hierarchy clean.",
      "source": "target",
